Here lies Raymond “Ray” Tse Jr, a Chinese-American teenager who had long-dreamed of owning a Mercedes-Benz. Unfortunately, while attending an exchange program in Hong Kong, Ray passed away at the age of 14 - just 2 years before he was set to secure his drivers license. His remains were sent home to New Jersey, where his older brother David, who had promised to purchase the car for him one day, commissioned a massive, single block of granite to be carved into a 1982 Mercedes-Benz 240 Diesel, which took the Rock of Ages Quarry of Graniteville, Vermont 18 months to materialize. After its completion in August of 1983, the Mercedes was installed behind the mausoleum where Ray is interred.

What if we kissed at the Colonial-era McDonald’s? Feast your eyes on the most beautiful @mcdonalds in America. Built in 1795, this was originally the home of Joseph Denton, a descendent of the town of Hempstead’s settlers (the Denton family owned a farm on several thousand acres of land, which is now known as Long Island’s New Hyde Park.) In 1986, McDonald’s bought the aging, boarded-up house with plans to level the property and build a restaurant on it’s prime location, only to face massive public outcry from the town who viewed the mansion as a historical landmark. Accordingly, after several years of petitioning, in 1988 the house was officially designated a historic site and McDonald’s, who had already purchased the land and property, was forced to restore the house where it still stands to this day - broken ice cream machine and all. #imlovinit

In 1630 the Burr family arrived to New York from England and purchased 166 acres of land in what’s presently known as Commack, Long Island. On this land they built a farm house, and out back they built their family cemetery. They buried their loved ones in the small plot of land until the 1880s, where the surrounding land eventually became the WW1 airfield known as Brindley Field. By the 1950s, the cemetery was surrounded by parking lot, where it still ages today in the shadow of a Home Depot.

The area now known as the City of Yarra stands on the traditional lands of the Wurundjeri people. Their connection to the land and its waterways extends back tens of thousands of years to the beginning of time when their creator spirit Bunjil formed the land and all living things.

The settlement and development of Melbourne impacted heavily on the Wurundjeri. From the 1830s, dispossession of land, dislocation, frontier clashes and introduced diseases led to a dramatic decline in the population. 

Despite the impacts of colonisation, the strong bonds between Wurundjeri families and clans could not be broken and the Wurundjeri remain active in the community today – practising culture, performing ceremonies and passing on knowledge to younger generations.

See: aboriginalhistoryofyarra.com.au

Scenes from a feature story in the June issue of Monocle on the future of underwater warfare.

A few months back I spent a week exploring Newport, Rhode Island, a small maritime town quickly becoming a world leader in naval development. Within a 5-mile radius lies the US Naval Undersea Warefare Center, the US Naval War College, and dozens of boat manufacture and tech start-ups all catering to the US Militaries’ demand for innovation. 

I’ll make several separate posts from the story in order to share more of these images with you - beginning with our time at the NUWC, a secretive, military installation perched on the eastern side of the bay. This site is not open to the public for obvious reasons - I’m told my invitation to photograph was rare and in fact, many of these spaces have been unseen by outside eyes until now.

For those curious, I was escorted by a large team my entire time beyond the gate. I had to receive permission for every shot, many of my requests turned down due to confidential information in a frame/background. I had to leave the cards and equipment on-site where the appropriate channels combed through my work and approved/denied the final files that were OK’d to share publicly. 

Christopher Lord did a fantastic job with this story, do give it a read. 

Big thanks to @mpbeaman for the call.

Scenes from a feature story in the June issue of Monocle on the future of underwater warfare.

A few months back I spent a week exploring Newport, Rhode Island, a small maritime town quickly becoming a world leader in naval development. Within a 5-mile radius lies the US Naval Undersea Warefare Center, the US Naval War College, and dozens of boat manufacture and tech start-ups all catering to the US Militaries’ demand for innovation. 

These images are from several local companies creating tech that is being licensed and utilized by the US Navy to aid in underwater combat and security. The first two slides are of a company called Jaia Robotics that create underwater, high speed drones. These Jaiabots provide recon as well as deliver payloads. They’re practically silent and can be sent out in packs of 15…I was shocked at how animalistic they felt as they effortlessly maneuvered through the crashing waves during our demo. 

Christopher Lord did a fantastic job with this story, do give it a read. 

Big thanks to @mpbeaman for the call.

Scenes from a feature story in the June issue of Monocle on the future of underwater warfare (final post).

A few months back I spent a week exploring Newport, Rhode Island, a small maritime town quickly becoming a world leader in naval development. Within a 5-mile radius lies the US Naval Undersea Warefare Center, the US Naval War College, and dozens of boat manufacture and tech start-ups all catering to the US Militaries’ demand for innovation. 

These images are from a day spent at the Naval War College, where we were fortunate to join in on a graduation ceremony. The NWC, which was founded in a coastline cottage in 1884, is now the Pentagon’s think-tank for US sea power. It’s a beautiful maritime campus with some fantastic old buildings - the portrait on slide 5 is in the original hall where the US naval war games began. It still has the same, original checkered floor where students play out different war scenarios like a game of Battleship. 

Christopher Lord did a fantastic job with this story, do give it a read. 

Big thanks to @mpbeaman for the call.

My wife’s uncle Steve has essentially devoted his entire existence to preserving native Australian land from outside forces be it disease, greedy developers, or some combination of the two. Steve is one of the smartest men I’ve met; his knowledge of dendrology, from the understory to the treetops, is quite frankly infinite. I had the pleasure of spending a weekend with him on his several hundred acres in a lush region called Highlands, where we spent hours overlanding through the growth in his Toyota #LandCruiser appropriately named Brutus. I saw many firsts while in Australia, from birds and critters I didn’t recognize, to some of the tallest eucalyptus trees I’ve ever seen. In fact, Wollemia pines (found in the wild only in Australia) are one of the most ancient tree species in the world, dating back some 200 million years. Earth would be a better place if more people like Steve existed.

In case you’ve been living under a rock, Maui is on fire with over 80% of Lahaina burned to ash. At least 50 (update: 100) people have died, and hundreds more have been displaced. For a town funded by tourism that only recently recovered from the effects of COVID, this fire will have long-lasting, devastating impact for the residents as well as the economy.

I was fortunate enough to have spent some time on Maui and in fact spent some quality time exploring Lahaina. The oldest Banyan tree in the US is in town, which I’m told is somehow expected to survive. My short week on Maui was unforgettable, a true Shangri-La in the middle of the ocean. 

I’m offering a limited edition print to support those affected by the fire, with all proceeds being donated to @hawaiicommunityfoundation’s #MauiStrong fund. The link to purchase is in my bio.

New work for @businessweek about a strange, magical place called Peachtree City. 

With about 9,300 golf carts registered among its 13,000 households, this town 31 miles southwest of Atlanta might be the most golf-cart-friendly municipality in America. A hundred miles of car-free multi-use paths crisscross the town’s 25 square miles, and many shopping centers and public buildings provide dedicated golf cart parking. A cartoon of one of the little vehicles appears on the town’s official logo.

I spent several days exploring Peachtree City (via golf cart, naturally) and can honestly say this might be the future of living independent of fossil fuels. In fact, most golf carts in Peachtree City are electric, with several public charging stations throughout. The entire city is accessible via golf cart; residents drive them to work, kids take them to school, you’re even able to take one straight through a Starbucks drive-thru. Smog-filled, freeway cities take note: there is an alternative to reducing your footprint. And as a personal added bonus, you can drive yourself from home straight onto the golf course. 

Great story by Eric Morrow, be sure to give it a read either online now or on newsstands next week.
